 "fibroblast", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8802708387374878, "span": {"begin": 770, "end": 780}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2147"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thrombin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954589605331421, "span": {"begin": 843, "end": 851}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:27035"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NOX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9761693477630615, "span": {"begin": 860, "end": 863}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:18421"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "superoxide superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9893844723701477, "span": {"begin": 874, "end": 895}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006861"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydrogen peroxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996741414070129, "span": {"begin": 906, "end": 923}}], "text": "The ROS released from the polymorphonuclear leucocytes following trauma and haemorrhagic shock led to lung injury and coagulopathy (Barrett CD et al., 2018). Serpin family A member 1 (SERPINA1/alpha-1-antitrypsin), a serine protease inhibitor, inhibits coagulation factor 2a (thrombin) (Cohen AB., 1973). SERPINA1 is a member of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and involved in ROS network (Lubrano V, and Balzan S. 2020). ROS are required for release of granzyme B (GzmB), a cytotoxic lymphocyte protease, into the cytosol (Mangan MS et al., 2016). SERPINA1 is converted into a ROS-sensitive granzyme B (GzmB) inhibitor by replacing the P4-P3&rsquo; reactive center loop residues (Mangan MS et al., 2016). Thrombin activates NADPH oxidase and produces ROS, which leads to fibroblast proliferation (Zhou SY et al., 2010). Endothelial exposure of thrombin induces NOX-dependent superoxide superoxide anion and hydrogen peroxide (Pai WY et al., 2017, Holland JA et al., 1998).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:32:04 +0000 2026"}